<subSubSection id="6BB46535FFD0FFE6FF6BA5E5FF463266" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="231136BEFFD0FFE6FF6BA5E5FEB330E5" blockId="23.[146,260,1471,1494]" box="[146,260,1471,1494]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<heading id="785981D2FFD0FFE6FF6BA5E5FEB330E5" box="[146,260,1471,1494]" fontSize="9" level="1" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" reason="6">
<taxonomicName id="E4AE4D3DFFD0FFE6FF6BA5E5FEB330E5" authorityName=", Eardley" authorityYear="2009" box="[146,260,1471,1494]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Schwarzia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="11DAEAACFFD0FFE6FF6BA5E5FEB330E5" box="[146,260,1471,1494]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Schwarzia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="231136BEFFD0FFE6FF6BA5B8FF463266" blockId="23.[146,771,1505,1936]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
In the initial description of 
<taxonomicName id="E4AE4D3DFFD0FFE6FE68A5BBFD3330C6" authority=", Eardley (2009)" authorityName=", Eardley" authorityYear="2009" box="[401,644,1505,1525]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Schwarzia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="11DAEAACFFD0FFE6FE68A5BBFE5930C6" box="[401,494,1505,1525]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Schwarzia</emphasis>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="473F4B4FFFD0FFE6FE03A5BBFD3330C6" author="Eardley, C." box="[506,644,1505,1525]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="65 - 68" refId="ref27087" refString="Eardley, C. 2009. First record of the tribe Biastini from the Afrotropical Region (Hymenoptera: Apidae). Zootaxa 2264: 65 - 68." type="journal article" year="2009">Eardley (2009)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
recognized it as 
<taxonomicName id="E4AE4D3DFFD0FFE6FF52A5A5FF473320" authorityName=", Linsley and Michener" authorityYear="1939" box="[171,240,1535,1555]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Biastini">Biastini</taxonomicName>
and proposed a particularly close relationship to 
<taxonomicName id="E4AE4D3DFFD0FFE6FD44A65AFD4A3321" baseAuthorityName="Roig-Alsina" baseAuthorityYear="1991" box="[701,765,1536,1554]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Biastes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="11DAEAACFFD0FFE6FD44A65AFD4A3321" box="[701,765,1536,1554]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Biastes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. This was a remarkably accurate assessment based on morphological examination, which we herein confirm with molecular data. In fact, 
<taxonomicName id="E4AE4D3DFFD0FFE6FF6BA60DFF583358" authorityName=", Eardley" authorityYear="2009" box="[146,239,1623,1643]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Schwarzia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="11DAEAACFFD0FFE6FF6BA60DFF583358" box="[146,239,1623,1643]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Schwarzia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is sister group to 
<taxonomicName id="E4AE4D3DFFD0FFE6FE60A602FE6E3359" baseAuthorityName="Roig-Alsina" baseAuthorityYear="1991" box="[409,473,1624,1642]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Biastes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="11DAEAACFFD0FFE6FE60A602FE6E3359" box="[409,473,1624,1642]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Biastes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as proposed above (
<figureCitation id="BB952A3BFFD0FFE6FD62A60DFD6F3358" box="[667,728,1623,1643]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[146,173,1616,1633]" captionTargetBox="[172,1425,150,1557]" captionTargetId="figure-3@4.[158,1429,146,1581]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 1. Fossil-calibrated chronogram of Neolarrini in the new sense (including Biastes, Neolarra, Rhopalolemma, Townsendiella and Schwarzia) based on 773 ultraconserved elements. Pie charts show possible ancestral ranges. Individual slices are scaled according to their probability as calculated through BioGeoBEARS. Bootstrap support (BS) values and posterior probabilities are omitted but correspond to 100 and 1.0 for all nodes, except for the branching of Oreopasites which has a lower BS value.Asterisks (*) indicate newly described species.Stem and crown ages of host taxa along the timeline on the left are taken from Cardinal et al. (2018). Scale bars next to specimen photographs indicate 2 mm length." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5384337" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5384337/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Figs. 1</figureCitation>
and 
<figureCitation id="BB952A3BFFD0FFE6FF6BA62EFF2933BB" box="[146,158,1652,1672]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="6.[146,173,1294,1311]" captionTargetBox="[160,1425,166,1257]" captionTargetId="figure-3@6.[160,1428,148,1259]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Fig. 2. Summary of phylogenetic relationships of Neolarrini with all described species, except for Neolarra. Solid lines show relationships estimated with molecular data and placements with dashed lines are derived from morphology or taxonomic information. Mapped diagnostic characters are listed in Table 3. Larval morphological characters are indicated by a gray background. Information on bee and floral hosts is taken from various sources (Michener 1936,Torchio et al. 1967, Krombein et al. 1979, Warncke 1981, Warncke 1982, Janzon and Svensson 1984, Westrich 1990, Rozen and McGinley 1991, Rozen et al. 1997, Bogusch 2003, Proshchalykin and Lelej 2004, Rozen et al. 2009, Orr and Griswold 2015, Scheuchl and Willner 2016, Westrich 2018). The higher classification of plants follows the APG IV system (The Angiosperm Phylogeny group 2016). Warncke (1982) also lists Systropha curvicornis and S. planidens as hosts of Biastes emarginatus but the source for this information is unclear and has been doubted by other authors (Westrich 2018). No host information is available for Schwarzia and species for which boxes are gray.Asterisks (*) indicate newly described species." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5384339" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5384339/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">2</figureCitation>
). In a second account of 
<taxonomicName id="E4AE4D3DFFD0FFE6FE60A62EFD3A33BB" authority=", Bossert (2019)" authorityName=", Bossert" authorityYear="2019" box="[409,653,1652,1672]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Schwarzia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="11DAEAACFFD0FFE6FE60A62EFE4133BB" box="[409,502,1652,1672]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Schwarzia</emphasis>
, Bossert (2019)
</taxonomicName>
described a second species and reevaluated the morphology of the genus. Some characters that were previously thought to be diagnostic for 
<taxonomicName id="E4AE4D3DFFD0FFE6FD44A6F5FCB533F0" authorityName=", Linsley and Michener" authorityYear="1939" box="[701,770,1711,1731]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Biastini">Biastini</taxonomicName>
(except 
<taxonomicName id="E4AE4D3DFFD0FFE6FF24A696FEDD33D3" authorityName="Roig-Alsina" authorityYear="1991" box="[221,362,1740,1760]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Rhopalolemma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="11DAEAACFFD0FFE6FF24A696FEDD33D3" box="[221,362,1740,1760]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Rhopalolemma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), such as the bidentate mandibles, did not hold up for the second species. However, other newly discovered features, including the reduced number of flagellomeres in males and the broad shape of the labrum, supported its morphological affinity to 
<taxonomicName id="E4AE4D3DFFD0FFE6FF52A718FF5C3267" baseAuthorityName="Roig-Alsina" baseAuthorityYear="1991" box="[171,235,1858,1876]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Biastes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="11DAEAACFFD0FFE6FF52A718FF5C3267" box="[171,235,1858,1876]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Biastes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="6BB46535FFD0FFE6FF4BA705FBF53753" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" type="description">
<paragraph id="231136BEFFD0FFE6FF4BA705FCB632A3" blockId="23.[146,771,1505,1936]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
The description of three new species of 
<taxonomicName id="E4AE4D3DFFD0FFE6FDD9A705FDCA3240" authorityName=", Bossert" authorityYear="2019" box="[544,637,1887,1907]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Schwarzia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="11DAEAACFFD0FFE6FDD9A705FDCA3240" box="[544,637,1887,1907]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Schwarzia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
herein demolishes one of these re-defined features. Both 
<taxonomicName id="E4AE4D3DFFD0FFE6FDDEA726FD6F32BC" authorityName="Bossert &amp; Copeland &amp; Sless &amp; Branstetter &amp; Gillung &amp; Brady &amp; Danforth &amp; Policarov치 &amp; Straka" authorityYear="2020" box="[551,728,1916,1936]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Schwarzia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="icipensis">
<emphasis id="11DAEAACFFD0FFE6FDDEA726FD6F32BC" box="[551,728,1916,1936]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Schwarzia icipensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="231136BEFFD0FFE6FCCBA0CEFBF53753" blockId="23.[818,1442,148,608]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<taxonomicName id="E4AE4D3DFFD0FFE6FCCBA0CEFC08359B" authorityName="Bossert &amp; Copeland &amp; Sless &amp; Branstetter &amp; Gillung &amp; Brady &amp; Danforth &amp; Policarov치 &amp; Straka" authorityYear="2020" box="[818,959,148,168]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Schwarzia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lualenyiensis">
<emphasis id="11DAEAACFFD0FFE6FCCBA0CEFC08359B" box="[818,959,148,168]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">S. lualenyiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
possess 11 flagellomeres in the male. Interestingly, there is also a single species of 
<taxonomicName id="E4AE4D3DFFD0FFE6FB78A0E8FB7635F7" baseAuthorityName="Roig-Alsina" baseAuthorityYear="1991" box="[1153,1217,178,196]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Biastes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="11DAEAACFFD0FFE6FB78A0E8FB7635F7" box="[1153,1217,178,196]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Biastes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with 11 flagellomeres (
<taxonomicName id="E4AE4D3DFFD0FFE6FCC0A08AFC0835D0" baseAuthorityName="Panzer" baseAuthorityYear="1798" box="[825,959,207,227]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Biastes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevicornis">
<emphasis id="11DAEAACFFD0FFE6FCC0A08AFC0835D0" box="[825,959,207,227]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">B. brevicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), whereas males of other 
<taxonomicName id="E4AE4D3DFFD0FFE6FB32A08AFABC35D1" baseAuthorityName="Roig-Alsina" baseAuthorityYear="1991" box="[1227,1291,208,226]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Biastes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="11DAEAACFFD0FFE6FB32A08AFABC35D1" box="[1227,1291,208,226]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Biastes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
possess 10. In 
<taxonomicName id="E4AE4D3DFFD0FFE6FCCBA0B6FC383433" authorityName=", Bossert" authorityYear="2019" box="[818,911,236,256]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Schwarzia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="11DAEAACFFD0FFE6FCCBA0B6FC383433" box="[818,911,236,256]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Schwarzia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, this trait is phylogenetically conserved, as species with 11 flagellomeres in males are sister taxa. The other three 
<taxonomicName id="E4AE4D3DFFD0FFE6FABCA153FCC43408" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Schwarzia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="11DAEAACFFD0FFE6FABCA153FA15342E" box="[1349,1442,265,285]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Schwarzia</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
, all of which have only 10 flagellomeres in the male, form the sister clade to this grouping (
<figureCitation id="BB952A3BFFD0FFE6FBCEA11EFBC5346B" box="[1079,1138,324,344]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[146,173,1616,1633]" captionTargetBox="[172,1425,150,1557]" captionTargetId="figure-3@4.[158,1429,146,1581]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 1. Fossil-calibrated chronogram of Neolarrini in the new sense (including Biastes, Neolarra, Rhopalolemma, Townsendiella and Schwarzia) based on 773 ultraconserved elements. Pie charts show possible ancestral ranges. Individual slices are scaled according to their probability as calculated through BioGeoBEARS. Bootstrap support (BS) values and posterior probabilities are omitted but correspond to 100 and 1.0 for all nodes, except for the branching of Oreopasites which has a lower BS value.Asterisks (*) indicate newly described species.Stem and crown ages of host taxa along the timeline on the left are taken from Cardinal et al. (2018). Scale bars next to specimen photographs indicate 2 mm length." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5384337" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5384337/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Figs. 1</figureCitation>
and 
<figureCitation id="BB952A3BFFD0FFE6FB67A11EFB1D346B" box="[1182,1194,324,344]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="6.[146,173,1294,1311]" captionTargetBox="[160,1425,166,1257]" captionTargetId="figure-3@6.[160,1428,148,1259]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Fig. 2. Summary of phylogenetic relationships of Neolarrini with all described species, except for Neolarra. Solid lines show relationships estimated with molecular data and placements with dashed lines are derived from morphology or taxonomic information. Mapped diagnostic characters are listed in Table 3. Larval morphological characters are indicated by a gray background. Information on bee and floral hosts is taken from various sources (Michener 1936,Torchio et al. 1967, Krombein et al. 1979, Warncke 1981, Warncke 1982, Janzon and Svensson 1984, Westrich 1990, Rozen and McGinley 1991, Rozen et al. 1997, Bogusch 2003, Proshchalykin and Lelej 2004, Rozen et al. 2009, Orr and Griswold 2015, Scheuchl and Willner 2016, Westrich 2018). The higher classification of plants follows the APG IV system (The Angiosperm Phylogeny group 2016). Warncke (1982) also lists Systropha curvicornis and S. planidens as hosts of Biastes emarginatus but the source for this information is unclear and has been doubted by other authors (Westrich 2018). No host information is available for Schwarzia and species for which boxes are gray.Asterisks (*) indicate newly described species." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5384339" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5384339/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">2</figureCitation>
). Based on this, we decided to continue assigning female first names only to those new species of 
<taxonomicName id="E4AE4D3DFFD0FFE6FCCBA125FC3834A0" authorityName=", Bossert" authorityYear="2019" box="[818,911,383,403]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Schwarzia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="11DAEAACFFD0FFE6FCCBA125FC3834A0" box="[818,911,383,403]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Schwarzia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
that exhibit this trait. We further reevaluated the shape of the labrum of 
<taxonomicName id="E4AE4D3DFFD0FFE6FC4AA1C6FBA73483" authorityName=", Bossert" authorityYear="2019" box="[947,1040,412,432]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Schwarzia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="11DAEAACFFD0FFE6FC4AA1C6FBA73483" box="[947,1040,412,432]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Schwarzia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and discovered a shared morphological feature with 
<taxonomicName id="E4AE4D3DFFD0FFE6FC77A1E0FC7934FF" baseAuthorityName="Roig-Alsina" baseAuthorityYear="1991" box="[910,974,442,460]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Biastes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="11DAEAACFFD0FFE6FC77A1E0FC7934FF" box="[910,974,442,460]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Biastes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In both 
<taxonomicName id="E4AE4D3DFFD0FFE6FBDFA1E0FBD134FF" baseAuthorityName="Roig-Alsina" baseAuthorityYear="1991" box="[1062,1126,442,460]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Biastes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="11DAEAACFFD0FFE6FBDFA1E0FBD134FF" box="[1062,1126,442,460]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Biastes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="E4AE4D3DFFD0FFE6FB6FA1E3FB4434FE" authorityName=", Bossert" authorityYear="2019" box="[1174,1267,441,461]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Schwarzia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="11DAEAACFFD0FFE6FB6FA1E3FB4434FE" box="[1174,1267,441,461]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Schwarzia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the apical margin of the labrum is straight, whereas it is medially prolonged and apically rounded or nearly pointed in all other 
<taxonomicName id="E4AE4D3DFFD0FFE6FB09A1AEFAE5373B" authorityName="Bossert &amp; Copeland &amp; Sless &amp; Branstetter &amp; Gillung &amp; Brady &amp; Danforth &amp; Policarov치 &amp; Straka" authorityYear="2020" box="[1264,1362,500,520]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" rank="tribe" tribe="Neolarrini">Neolarrini</taxonomicName>
. Besides these features, we report seven diagnostic characters for the genus 
<taxonomicName id="E4AE4D3DFFD0FFE6FCCBA275FC383770" authorityName=", Bossert" authorityYear="2019" box="[818,911,559,579]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Schwarzia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="11DAEAACFFD0FFE6FCCBA275FC383770" box="[818,911,559,579]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Schwarzia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, nearly half of which stem from the terminal segments of the female metasoma (
<figureCitation id="BB952A3BFFD0FFE6FBF8A216FB823753" box="[1025,1077,588,608]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="6.[146,173,1294,1311]" captionTargetBox="[160,1425,166,1257]" captionTargetId="figure-3@6.[160,1428,148,1259]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Fig. 2. Summary of phylogenetic relationships of Neolarrini with all described species, except for Neolarra. Solid lines show relationships estimated with molecular data and placements with dashed lines are derived from morphology or taxonomic information. Mapped diagnostic characters are listed in Table 3. Larval morphological characters are indicated by a gray background. Information on bee and floral hosts is taken from various sources (Michener 1936,Torchio et al. 1967, Krombein et al. 1979, Warncke 1981, Warncke 1982, Janzon and Svensson 1984, Westrich 1990, Rozen and McGinley 1991, Rozen et al. 1997, Bogusch 2003, Proshchalykin and Lelej 2004, Rozen et al. 2009, Orr and Griswold 2015, Scheuchl and Willner 2016, Westrich 2018). The higher classification of plants follows the APG IV system (The Angiosperm Phylogeny group 2016). Warncke (1982) also lists Systropha curvicornis and S. planidens as hosts of Biastes emarginatus but the source for this information is unclear and has been doubted by other authors (Westrich 2018). No host information is available for Schwarzia and species for which boxes are gray.Asterisks (*) indicate newly described species." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5384339" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5384339/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
